  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Initially addressed through tax evasion and financial crime laws\n\n2. Key Milestone - Bank Secrecy Act (1970):\n- First comprehensive U.S. legislation targeting financial transactions\n- Required banks to report large cash transactions\n- Established framework for tracking potential illicit financial activities\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1980s: Growing international concern about drug trafficking proceeds\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention introduced first comprehensive international standards\n- Encouraged nations to criminalize money laundering related to drug trade\n\n4. Major Expansion - Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Laws:\n- 1990s: Broader financial crime regulations\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established international standards\n- Expanded beyond drug-related crimes to broader criminal proceeds\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Strengthened reporting requirements\n- Enhanced connections between money laundering and terrorism financing\n- Increased international cooperation\n\n6. Contemporary Challenges:\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Digital transaction tracking\n- Complex international financial networks\n\nThe framework continues evolving with technological and financial innovations.",
